tip.text:
This gem of a cafe is a welcome addition to Hackney serving up delicious coffee blends in a minimal and airy space adorned with retro stylings. It's just the kind of cafe you'd expect to find in such ends: calm, white walls, full of people doing things on their laptops that are innumerably more important than whatever you are doing on yours.

They pride themselves on their coffee here, so kick things off with a cup of joe, while you decide whether their brunch menu is tempting enough to hang around for. Sourdough bread, slow-roast beans, fried mushrooms and prosciutto topped with poached eggs sure worked on us.

There‚Äôs a definite beauty in simple pleasures. Kicking back and listening to wax spin while you sip on a coffee has got to be one of those: swing by here and listen to records in a supremely chilled setting, with coffee from the delightful roasters at All Press and fresh juices on the menu to boot. Drinks might get a little bit stiffer once the sun goes down but you won‚Äôt find us complaining about that.

It's a well known fact that judging a cafe around this area is partly to do with the quality and value of the food but mainly down to its aesthetic value. Insta is important and you really ought not forget that. Cafe Miami, situated in the beautiful, rather incongruous listed Strand Building brings a nice dose of Art Deco to Clapton, with its pastel hues, retro furnishings and Americana specialities.

The main talking point is probably the interior - plenty of phones come out at this place - and, to be honest, the food is nothing above your usual brunch fare; albeit with some Miami-inspired decadence. Waffle burgers with chorizo, avocado and fried egg; fish finger tacos; and hot honey smoked salmon with ricotta on focaccia all promise plenty of richness and come in around the ¬£9 mark.

That vegan cafe in Bethnal Green everyone is raving about. You've heard of it. We're sure you have. It's 100% vegan, community run and not for profit. Get your vegan samosas, sausage rolls, cakes and milkshakes, or go for a posh coffee.

You can also buy produce to take away, including vegan cheeses, faux meats, tofu, tempeh, Club Mate & Fritz Kola (German drinks), as well as politically-charged vegan cookbooks. Because you never know when you might need one. Hell, you could probably use one right now.

It's like Britain and Japan got into a fight, made up, then opened up a cafe together. Pacific Social Club describes itself as a drop-out centre and wannabe Izakaya. What does that mean for you? Great coffee and cakes to the soundtrack of vintage vinyls by day, but in the evenings from Thursday to Saturday you have the mighty Japanese Sho Foo Doh kitchen takeover.

We don't know how they came up with this intercontinental mix, but we wish there were more like it.

To all those who think vegans don't do it indulgent we present: We Are Vegan Everything. A very Insta friendly, Bali-vibes brunch spot and cafe in Hackney that's doing mighty, naughty things with plant-based food. We came in for brunch and were really damn satisfied by both the sweet (blueberry pancakes and vegan coconut cream) and savoury (sourdough topped with tomatoes, mushrooms and avocado). It feels like the kind of place an Australian wellness influencer in Bali would have created, and we mean that in a nice way. The freakshake, meanwhile, is one of the most rich and decadent shakes we've ever sampled.

This quaint little cafe is not geographically constrained by its Hackney location, and serves up some top notch platters focussing on cuisines from all over. From Latino, Scandinavian, Oriental, Middle Eastern, American... it's pretty much got it all. Oh, and they're all only ¬£7.50. Despite the worldly dishes, they've still got that Hackney community vibe, with convivial seating, regular supper clubs and local artwork plastered on the walls.

If you only feel peckish, the tea here is pretty fuckin' delightful, served in cute tea-sets, pots and saucers, all sourced from local junk shops. Service can be a tad slow, but it's more because they're overwhelmed, and not because they're rude and cba, so we feel mean for even bringing it up.

Imagine if Wes Anderson and Marie Antoinette had a love child, and that love child had a popular lifestyle blog in Palm Springs and was Instagram famous. That's the general vibe at Palm Vault, Hackney's (and we'd be willing to bet the world's) most aesthetically pleasing cafe.

With low hanging plants suspended from the ceiling, exposed brick, and a pastel colour scheme that puts Ladur√©e to shame, the atmosphere here will have you seeing la vie en rose. Oh, and the food is pretty great too, concentrating on locally-sourced plant based dishes that have inspired songs in the hearts of the Hackney vegan community. A must-try (for the 'gram as much as for the taste) is their fuchsia-hued velvet latte, which is made from beetroot and steamed milk (your choice from an extensive list of vegan substitutes). We also loved the avocado chocolate cake, and will never stop being mesmerised by the colour-changing "Magick Tea" which is nothing short of sorcery.

Homerton seems to have had a makeover recently and Hatch has definitely had a part to play in it. Converted from a warehouse into a multi purpose space, Hatch's spacious and thoughtfully designed space houses an all-day cafe, juice bar and plenty of hot desks - perfect place to get those creative juices flowing. Check the website to get informed on all the tasty art workshops, talks, film nights and events from local creatives.

Food-wise they've pretty much got everything that might tickle your fancy. Vanilla and cinnamon waffle? Yup. Bean and roasted red pepper quesadilla? Tick. Mediterranean grilled halloumi flatbread with beetroot and tzatziki? Oh you betta believe it, sugar. They've also got a fab selection of booze, and a bangin' Happy Hour 5-7pm.

When you heard the chaps behind the Sebright Arms were opening up a restaurant you were excited, right? So were we. And our instincts were right because The Vincent is a very decent all-day brunch & cocktail spot perfect for doing a bit of indulging, offering a bit of a rarity in these parts: substantial bang for your buck.

In a calming wooden oasis featuring big teak lanterns and banana trees, this is a perfect hangover or lazy weekend affair. The menu spans from the healthy to the downright decadent, with classic breakfast offerings joined by stuff like veggie hash, fried chicken and waffle, and their famous bunsmith buns filled with fried chicken or cheeseburgers. But whatever you do, save some space for their waffle with berries and cream - we got it thinking we only wanted a bite, and before we knew it our plate was licked clean.

listing.name: Dark Arts Coffee / I Will Kill Again
listing.subtitle: Roastery and Cafe

tip.text:
Some sort of enigmatic magic is afoot in a railway arch in Homerton, where an alluring mishmash of the occult, biker culture and insanely good coffee is turning people a little bit crazy - although it could just be that jitter juice. A roastery during the week (Dark Arts Coffee); a vegan-orientated cafe on the weekends (I Will Kill Again), we rate this as a really memorable place to do the coffee and brunch thing in East.

The coffee is dangerously moreish: beans from all over the world that are uniquely blended into something so damn creamy you can almost taste the threat of your own demise. The brunch, meanwhile, is of the quality to have vegans and non-vegans alike rushing down to get into plates that artfully combine smoked tempeh rashers, crispy potato rosti and sweet sun-dried tomatoes to create something greater than the sum of their parts. Throw in a chilled ambience with laid-back, black-clad owners dripping with cool, and you have yourself a spot that walks the walk and talks the talk.

Isreali-inspired Bernstein‚Äôs Bar is a slice of Tel-Aviv cool sitting on a corner of Chatsworth Road. This is an ideal place to take a seat (inside or on the pavement) and watch the Clapton cool cats pass whilst tucking into hearty Middle Eastern dishes; having a coffee; doing the lazy lunch dance; or dipping the beak in something strong and letting the evening take over.

Sourcing plenty of their bits locally, the cuisine here is the comforting chow of Israel and the Levant: fish, meat and cheese sharing boards alongside filling and tasty soups - the chicken stew is known to cure almost every illness known to man. Serving all sorts for all sorts, it‚Äôs another vibey spot to add to Clapton‚Äôs growing arsenal.

We lament the fall of the tram as much as the next app, but that cloud has a silver lining because the old Clapton Tram Depot has been superbly converted into a soothing, beautiful caf√© full of botany, exposed brickwork, ancient beams and parquetry flooring. The owners of this place have really put some time into the aesthetic and we're digging it. They serve breakfast, lunch and also sell a range of organic products from this light-filled space.

Whilst the lunch menu features a couple of toasted sandwiches and a soup of the day, we stopped by for a lazy breakfast where the menu comes with all the classics: Bloody Mary, sourdough, granola, eggs, bacon. Whatever you do, though, get a dish featuring their portobello mushrooms in tarragon and soya cashew cream - you won't regret it. With soft piano music playing overhead, and locals reading the paper and having a chat, this is a green oasis of calm in Clapton.

Venetia's is the type of place you'd be happy to stumble upon while out on a stroll. Small and inviting, it's a decent addition to the neighbourhood. Look at for their spacious back patio.

Sandwiches are the name of the game here - and they make a satisfying, quick lunch. You'll find classic paninis alongside more creative sourdough options, like the halloumi and chorizo with roast peppers and hummus.

Don‚Äôt fall for the 60s worker‚Äôs-cafe exterior - Jim‚Äôs is a modern brunching spot through and through, gimmicky warts and all. What some lesser publications might call ‚Äòhipster‚Äô, gimmicks come by way of the Black Skulls, the motorcycle ‚Äòlifestyle brand‚Äô that have taken over the residence with leathers on the walls and motorbike parts dotted about. As much as we‚Äôd like to sneer, the aesthetic meshes quite well with the retro wood-panelled diner vibe.

From bircher muesli to juicy, pink double cheese burgers, this is an all-day dining affair, but for us it‚Äôs gotta be brunch, when classics like kedgeree, salt beef hash, and kippers come into play - all done with the kind of finesse you'd associate with a more formal setting. Wash it down with an expertly crafted bloody mary (read: strong) and you‚Äôve got yourself a breakfast-lunch mash-up fit for a king - or at least the boss of a Hackney biker gang.

Sometimes you just gotta do the laundry, and sometimes it just takes a while. Well, it‚Äôd be nice if you could chill and sip a coffee while you wait‚Ä¶ Oh, hang on, you can totes do that here!

Chatsworth Launderette is a properly singular hangout, the sort of spot that makes you fall in love with London right over again. Run by a charming rasta, coffees here only cost a couple bob and they even get chairs out front in the summer. Shit, we‚Äôll be muddying our garments on purpose in that case. See you there.

Clapton‚Äôs departure from its ‚Äòmurder mile‚Äô days has been worryingly speedy, there‚Äôs no way this time a decade ago you‚Äôd have found a burger bar like Eat 17 on the end of Chatsworth Road. Gentrification woes aside, this place is actually really delicious. It‚Äôs not uncommon to find queuing punters spilling out onto the road come Saturday night, which probably has something to do with the juicy af meats and sexy lunch boxes being dished out here. Oh and that homemade cookie-dough ice cream is bound to have you ice-screaming for more within seconds.

Lurking beneath a pair of east London railway arches is this electric little haunt championing the holy trinity of cool - coffee, motorbikes and leather. Bolt is a creative space celebrating all thinks biker, selling motorcycle gear and brewing coffee off the back of a Vespa. Head down to check out their huge range of leather bikerwear and keep your eye on their sosh media for future deals and exhibitions.

Sure you've been in your fair share of cafes, but not one quite like this. Owner Aidan, an avid collector and lover of all things natural history, has lovingly (and painstakingly) created a cafe-cum-miniature-natural-history-museum and it's a transportive, singular experience - as close to the cupboard-into-Narnia flex as it's possible to get. From the luxey pastel pink and creme hues; to the foraged branches and moss; to the surreal taxidermy sitting proud, it's an aesthetic rarity - and a reminder that sometimes fetishes can be a good thing.

With the layout of a small gallery, glass cabinets are filled with all manner of fossils, bones, artefacts and specimens. All for sale; all worthy of a momentary browse. And if that tummy starts to rumble, you'll find coffees, cakes and a short breakfast and lunch menu with carefully put together dishes such as Ottolenghi home-baked beans, salsa and beetroot yoghurt on sourdough; manchego and cheddar toastie with truffle oil; or slow roasted garlic and thyme mushrooms on toast. Keep an eye out for a cute garden out back too.

When a place develops a cult following, it's only right to pay it a little attention and wonder what all the fuss is about. The kind of place where owners know their customers on first name terms, this tiny little hut might be short on space but it's big on character as all manner of locals drop in for their caffeine fix. That fix comes courtesy of Square Mile's Red Brick beans, whilst E5 Bakehouse provide the bread for the sandwiches and gluten-free cakes.

There are only 5 tables here, so don't go expecting a sit down and catch up. Stop by, have a little chat, and be on your way. You've got shit to do, remember?
